## Testing

### What Requires Tests
- [ ] All business logic functions
- [ ] All API endpoints (at least happy path + main error cases)
- [ ] All data transformations
- [ ] <Any other required coverage>

### Test Structure
```<language>
# Naming: describe what it does, not what it is
# BAD:  test("processUser")
# GOOD: test("processUser returns null when user is inactive")

describe("<unit under test>", () => {
  describe("<scenario>", () => {
    it("<expected outcome>", () => {
      // Arrange
      // Act
      // Assert
    });
  });
});
```

### Mocking Rules
- <e.g., Mock at the boundary (HTTP clients, DB) — never mock business logic>
- <e.g., Use factories for test data, not hardcoded literals>
- <e.g., Integration tests run against a real DB (use test DB)>

---

## Async / Concurrency

- <e.g., Always use async/await over raw Promises>
- <e.g., Never use Promise.all without handling individual rejections>
- <e.g., All background jobs must be idempotent>

---

## Logging

```<language>
# Use structured logging — always include context keys
logger.info("Order processed", { orderId, userId, amount })

# NOT this:
console.log("Order " + orderId + " processed")
```

- **Log levels:** DEBUG (local dev only) | INFO (state transitions) | WARN (recoverable issues) | ERROR (needs attention)
- **Never log:** passwords, tokens, PII, full request bodies
- **Always log:** request IDs, user/entity IDs, durations for slow operations

---

## Security Conventions

- **Input validation:** <e.g., validate at the API boundary using Zod/Pydantic/Joi — never trust request data>
- **SQL:** <e.g., parameterized queries only — no string concatenation>
- **Secrets:** <e.g., never hardcode, always read from environment — use .env.example for docs>
- **Auth checks:** <e.g., always verify at the service layer, not just middleware>
- **Dependencies:** <e.g., run `npm audit` / `pip-audit` before merging>

